---
/**
 * context-engineering 0008 · Figure 3 — Module 2 "why approximate?": exact k-NN
 * scans all n (100% recall, O(n), slow) vs ANN probing a region (~95% recall,
 * sub-linear, fast).
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from
 * docs/context-engineering/lessons/0008-embeddings-indexing-and-cost.html.
 * Lives as an .astro component (not inline MDX) because raw inline SVG with
 * kebab-case attributes is unreliable in MDX but is plain HTML in .astro. This
 * figure references no shared arrowhead markers, so it needs no <defs>.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 600 200"
        role="img"
        aria-label="Exact search scans all vectors and is slow; approximate search probes a small region and is fast with slightly lower recall."
    >
        <!-- exact -->
        <text x="150" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >Exact k-NN — scan all n</text
        >
        <rect x="30" y="30" width="240" height="60" rx="6" fill="#fbecec" stroke="#9a2417"></rect>
        <circle cx="55" cy="50" r="4" fill="#6b675f"></circle><circle
            cx="80"
            cy="65"
            r="4"
            fill="#6b675f"></circle><circle cx="105" cy="48" r="4" fill="#6b675f"></circle><circle
            cx="130"
            cy="70"
            r="4"
            fill="#6b675f"></circle><circle cx="160" cy="52" r="4" fill="#6b675f"></circle><circle
            cx="190"
            cy="68"
            r="4"
            fill="#6b675f"></circle><circle cx="220" cy="50" r="4" fill="#6b675f"></circle><circle
            cx="245"
            cy="66"
            r="4"
            fill="#6b675f"></circle>
        <text x="150" y="108" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#9a2417"
            >100% recall · O(n) · too slow at scale</text
        >
        <!-- approx -->
        <text x="450" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >ANN — probe a region</text
        >
        <rect x="330" y="30" width="240" height="60" rx="6" fill="#e9f3ec" stroke="#2f5d3a"></rect>
        <circle cx="355" cy="50" r="4" fill="#cfcac2"></circle><circle
            cx="380"
            cy="65"
            r="4"
            fill="#cfcac2"></circle><circle cx="405" cy="48" r="4" fill="#2f5d3a"></circle><circle
            cx="430"
            cy="70"
            r="4"
            fill="#2f5d3a"></circle><circle cx="460" cy="52" r="4" fill="#2f5d3a"></circle><circle
            cx="490"
            cy="68"
            r="4"
            fill="#cfcac2"></circle><circle cx="520" cy="50" r="4" fill="#cfcac2"></circle><circle
            cx="545"
            cy="66"
            r="4"
            fill="#cfcac2"></circle>
        <rect
            x="395"
            y="40"
            width="78"
            height="40"
            rx="5"
            fill="none"
            stroke="#2f5d3a"
            stroke-dasharray="4 3"></rect>
        <text x="450" y="108" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >~95% recall · sub-linear · scans a fraction</text
        >
        <!-- verdict -->
        <text x="300" y="150" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >Give up a few percent recall &rarr; orders-of-magnitude faster queries</text
        >
        <text x="300" y="172" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-style="italic" fill="#6b675f"
            >recall = fraction of the true top-k the index actually returns</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        ANN is a deliberate bargain: the "approximate" means it occasionally misses a true
        neighbour. For retrieval that's usually fine — a reranker (Lesson 2) cleans up the top, and
        95% recall at 1ms beats 100% at 500ms.<sup><a href="#s3" id="r4b">3</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
